The following will work using `forEach` and `computeIfAbsent`:

    Map&lt;Integer, List&lt;Integer&gt;&gt; personByAge = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();
    m.forEach((k, v) -&gt; personByAge.computeIfAbsent(v, ArrayList::new).add(k));

It would probably be better to use a `Set` for the multiple type as there will be no guarantee of order when iterating over the `Map`, and the keys are already unique. 

This is essentially implementing the equivalent of `flip` which is included in [Eclipse Collections][1] on `MutableMap`. The difference is that `flip` returns a `MutableSetMultimap`. The following is an example using `flip`. 

    MutableMap&lt;Integer, Integer&gt; m = Maps.mutable.empty();
    m.put(1, 1);
    m.put(2, 1);
    m.put(3, 1);
    m.put(4, 2);
    m.put(5, 2);
    m.put(6, 2);
    m.put(7, 2);
    MutableSetMultimap&lt;Integer, Integer&gt; personByAge = m.flip();
    System.out.println(personByAge);

Output:

    {1=[1, 2, 3], 2=[4, 5, 6, 7]}

Because `flip` returns a `SetMultimap`, it is easier to write test assertions because order won&#39;t matter on the multi value. For example. the following test can be written for this example.

    SetMultimap&lt;Integer, Integer&gt; personByAge = m.flip();

    SetMultimap&lt;Integer, Integer&gt; expected =
        Multimaps.mutable.set.&lt;Integer, Integer&gt;empty()
            .withKeyMultiValues(1, 3, 2, 1)
            .withKeyMultiValues(2, 7, 5, 6, 4);
    Assertions.assertEquals(expected, personByAge);

If your source is a JDK `HashMap`, and you want to use Streams, the following will implement the equivalent of `flip` using `Collectors2` from Eclipse Collections.

    SetMultimap&lt;Integer, Integer&gt; personByAge = m.entrySet().stream()
        .collect(Collectors2.toSetMultimap(Map.Entry::getValue, Map.Entry::getKey));

    SetMultimap&lt;Integer, Integer&gt; expected =
        Multimaps.mutable.set.&lt;Integer, Integer&gt;empty()
            .withKeyMultiValues(1, 3, 2, 1)
            .withKeyMultiValues(2, 7, 5, 6, 4);
    Assertions.assertEquals(expected, personByAge);

Note: I am a committer for Eclipse Collections.

  [1]: https://github.com/eclipse/eclipse-collections

